[2]
Date: Tue 22 Dec 2009
From: David Thomson <thomson.david48@gmail.com> [edited]


I am in general agreement with the WHO briefing note. It is important
to recognize also that when a pandemic virus like pandemic influenza
(H1N1) 2009 virus has an atypical pattern of occurrence relative to
time, such as one or more recurrent spring/summer/fall waves, it
complicates assessment of extra influenza-related mortalities because
the 'rest of the year' picture is complicated relative to the one
that usually prevails for strictly seasonal influenza.

Also it is very important not to lose sight of the fact that
'mortality' is far from the only significant adverse impact of any
highly infectious disease like influenza. Unfortunately, direct
objective measurement of these other adverse impacts is usually far
more complicated and difficult than measurement of mortalities. The
popular media often tends to bias its considerations towards the more
visibly extreme outcomes (mortalities) and the simpler things that
can be more readily and widely grasped by the 'public'.

--
David Thomson
Animal Health Specialist
Secretariat of the Pacific Community
<thomson.david48@gmail.com>
